outcomes.title: Experimental Studies
outcomes.description: I can identify and analyze key elements of experiments.
outcomes.template:
Scenario:

A recent study examined whether meditation can be used to counter the impact of math anxiety. {{n}} {{age}} were randomly assigned to one of two groups. Both groups were given information to read about why some people have math anxiety. Then, students in the first group completed a 5-minute meditation. Students in the second group did not do the meditation. Both groups then took a math test. The tests were graded by a math TA (not related to the researchers) {{blinding}}. The results were that students in the meditation group scored {{diff}}% higher that the students in the non-mediation group. {{results}}.

Describe the control group.

The half of the {{n}}, {{age}} that did not meditate before the test

What is the explanatory variable?

The meditation

What were the results of the study?

The group that meditated before the test did {{diff}}% better

Did the researchers use any blinding? if so, what was blinded?

{{answer_4}}

Are the results generalizable to all adults?

No, answers will vary

outcomes.title: Statistical Graphs
outcomes.template:
A critical component to our understanding of statistics is being able to read and understand graphs. It is also critical that we be able to look at graphs and identify any flaws they might have. Be sure to answer ALL the questions.

Percentage of smokers by household income

Use the graph above to answer the questions.

What type of graph is this?

bar graph

Could you use a {{graph_2}} graph to display this data? Why or why not?

No, {{answer_2}}

What percent of people whose household income is {{money_3}} smoke "every day" or "some days"? What information in the graph tells you this answer?

{{answer_3}}%, the number inside the bar.

What does the number in the bar in the {{money_4}} line mean in the context of the information presented by the graph?

Out of the households that make {{money_4}}, {{answer_4}}% of them has someone that smokes some or every day in them.

What is the trend in the percent of people who smoke "every day" or "some days" as household income {{dir_5}}? Justify your answer with evidence from the graph.

As the household income level {{dir_5}}, the percentage of smoker in the income level {{answer_5}}
